\begin_layout Subsection
Risk Measurement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Possible future values are typically described in terms of the 
\series bold
probability distribution
\series default
 of the likelihood of possible outcomes.
 This concept is rather theoretical, as usually this distribution is not
 observed in reality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In theory: look at the possible rated of return and the possibility of each
 one, find out the 
\series bold
expected return
\series default
 and the 
\series bold
variance
\series default
.
 The standard deviation is called 
\series bold
volatility
\series default
 in the finance jargon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the SD to measure uncertainity is advantageous, because:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It measures how spreadout is the realized rate of return around its expectation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Differences around the mean are squared, thus large ones are more significant
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
SD and the expected rate of return are in the same unit of measure.
\end_layout

