\begin_layout Subsection
Correlation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Correlation coefficient
\series default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ab}$
\end_inset

, is the extent to which two securities move together.
 It is a statistical measure, between -1 and 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The correlation is given by the covariance, divided by the standard deviation
 (volatility):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{ab}=\frac{\sigma_{ab}}{\sigma_{a}\sigma_{b}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formula can be rewritten:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma^{2}(x_{a}a+x_{b}b)=x_{a}^{2}\sigma_{a}^{2}+x_{b}^{2}\sigma_{b}^{2}+2x_{a}x_{b}\rho_{ab}\sigma_{a}\sigma_{b}
\]

\end_inset

It can be seen that a variance in each security introduces variance of the
 whole portfolio, but the last term might be negative (when 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ab}<0$
\end_inset

) and cancel out some of that variance.
\end_layout

